why public folder outside app, what it has
ChatGPT said:
Great question â€” and this one is important for understanding how Next.js handles static assets.

Letâ€™s make it very clear:

â­ Why the public/ folder is outside the app/ folder
Because public/ is not part of routing, and not controlled by the App Router.

It is a static asset folder that Next.js exposes directly at the root URL (/).

So:

/public/logo.png
is served at:

https://your-website.com/logo.png
regardless of whatâ€™s inside the app/ folder.

ğŸ—‚ï¸ What goes in public/?
Everything that:

âœ”ï¸ must be publicly accessible
âœ”ï¸ should NOT be bundled by Webpack or Vite
âœ”ï¸ should NOT be imported directly into components
âœ”ï¸ should not trigger Next.js transformations
Typical examples:

1ï¸âƒ£ Images
Logos, backgrounds, icons, OpenGraph images:

public/logo.png
public/bg.jpg
public/icons/user.svg
2ï¸âƒ£ Static files
public/robots.txt
public/sitemap.xml
public/manifest.json
3ï¸âƒ£ Downloadable files
public/files/terms.pdf
public/files/app.apk
4ï¸âƒ£ Favicons
public/favicon.ico
public/apple-touch-icon.png
public/icon.png
â­ Why isn't public/ inside the app/ folder?
Because:

It must be at the root of the Next.js app folder

Next.js needs it at build time

Assets inside public are not processed by the bundler

App Router folders (app/) are for routes and components, not static assets

So Next.js architecture is:

web/
  app/        <-- pages, layouts, components
  public/     <-- static files, not compiled
  src/        <-- reusable code
The App Router has nothing to do with public/.

â­ When should you put images in public/?
Use public/ when:

âœ”ï¸ You need a file to be available at a public URL
Example: OG images:

<meta property="og:image" content="/og-image.png" />
âœ”ï¸ You use the <Image> component with a fixed file path
<Image src="/logo.png" width={100} height={50} />
âœ”ï¸ You donâ€™t want bundling or hashing
Assets stay exactly as-is.

âœ”ï¸ You need stable URLs for crawlers or external access
(e.g., robots.txt, favicon.ico)

âŒ When not to use public/?
Do NOT put component-specific images in public.

Better:

import MyImg from '@/assets/foo.png'
or with /app/:

<Image src="/images/foo.png" />
ğŸ§  Summary Table
Folder	Purpose	Managed by	Behaves like
app/	Routes, layouts, server & client components	Next.js App Router	React + routing
src/	Reusable code, UI components, hooks	Webpack/Vite	Normal code
public/	Raw static assets (images, txt, xml)	Node/static server	Static files
ğŸ‰ Final answer
The public folder is outside app/ because it contains static assets, not routes.
Next.js serves everything in public/ as raw files at the root URL, completely separate from routing logic.

